  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Youth training and psychosocial support 2017-18</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Lebanon&apos;s Roumieh prison youth wing is experiencing massive overcrowding, with young people being detained (often without charge) for years on char
Since 2013, the influx of Syrian refugees has had major repercussions on the minor section (11-21) in Roumieh prison due to the increase in cases of Syrian minors being arrested and detained. Today, Syrian minors make up around 60% of the inmate population.
This project will continue providing services in order to protect vulnerable adolescents who face social exclusion often before they enter the prison as well as after they leave. By providing direct support to targeted inmates, MS and the prison service can support them to make good use of their sentence, to address gaps in their skills, to improve their employability and to change their personal attitudes and perceptions &#x2013; including the development of new perceptions and attitudes which can help them to understand the reasons for and consequences of their actions.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is a continuation of the 2016-2017 CA funded MSL intervention in Roumieh prison. It will provide psychosocial, socio-economic and juridical support for 120 young male (45-50% Syrians, 50-65% Lebanese and other nationalities) inmates currently inside Roumieh minor section and provide specific accompaniment to 60 recently released adolescent prisoners to help them reintegrate into society and avoid being victims of discrimination, abuse and re-offending through family support, in-house visits, individual social and psychological support, legal counselling and employability counselling.</narrative>
  </description>
